Boil a full #kettle{} of water.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the onion and cook until starting to soften, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

For the last ~{2%minutes}, add the @peas{120%g} to the pan.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

While the rice cooks, add the @diced chicken breast{260%g} to the frying pan with the onion and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Fry until the chicken is golden brown and cooked through and the onion is golden and soft, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the chicken is cooked, stir in the garlic and @ground coriander{1%tsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}, @cajun spice mix{1%tbsp} (add less if you'd prefer things milder), @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water for the sauce{100%ml}.

Stir together and bring to the boil, then simmer until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the cooked rice and peas to chicken pan.

Add a knob of @?butter{} (if you have any) and stir to combine.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if needed.

When ready, share your dirty rice between your #bowls{}.

Top with a dollop of @soured cream{75%g} to finish.

Enjoy!